$section Windows Installation and Testing$$

$head Download Current Version$$
$index download, windows$$
If you are using 
$href%
	http://www.cygwin.com%
	Cygwin
%$$
or,
$href%
	http://www.mingw.org%
	MinGW with MSYS
%$$,
with Unix formatted files,
just follow all of the $xref/InstallUnix//Unix installation/$$ steps.
Otherwise,
download the file
$href%
	http://www.coin-or.org/Tarballs/CppAD/CppAD-06-08-02.zip%
	CppAD-06-08-02.zip
%$$

$head Extraction$$
Use 
$href%
	http://www.winzip.com%
	WinZip
%$$
or some other program to decompress the archive
$code CppAD-06-08-02.zip$$.
This will create the distribution directory 
$syntax%
	cppad-06-08-02
%$$
All the command sequences below assume that you start in this
distribution directory.
If you are using Cygwin, or MinGW with MSYS, (with dos file formats)
you should follow the $xref/InstallUnix//Unix installation/$$ steps
for the rest of the install.
Otherwise, continue with the steps below:

$head User Documentation$$
The $code Doc$$ sub-directory of the distribution directory
contains user documentation for CppAD.
The files $syntax%Doc/%*%.htm%$$ are in HTML format.
If your browser supports XHTML+MATHML format,
an easier to read copy is available in the files
$syntax%Doc/%*%.xml%$$.

$head Developer Documentation$$
The $code Dev$$ sub-directory of the distribution directory
contains developer documentation for CppAD. 

$head Getting Started$$
$index GetStarted, windows$$
The following steps will build the $xref/GetStarted.cpp/$$ example.
Using Microsoft Visual C++,
open the workspace $code GetStarted/GetStarted.sln$$
in Visual Studio and then select $code Build | Build GetStarted.exe$$.
Then in a Dos box, execute the following commands
$codep
	cd GetStarted\Debug
	GetStarted
$$

$head Introduction$$
$index introduction, windows$$
The following steps will build the routines that verify the calculations
in the $xref/Introduction/$$ section.
Using Microsoft Visual C++,
open the workspace $code Introduction/Introduction.sln$$ in Visual Studio.
Then select $code Build | Build Introduction.exe$$.
Then in a Dos box, execute the following commands
$codep
	cd Introduction\Debug
	Introduction
$$

